issue.body:
* Branch: https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/tree/slicing
* Diff: https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/compare/master...slicing

# `DataFlowView`

* [x] List 
* [x] Allow switching between `value` and `access`
* [x] Allow filtering: `Read`, `Write`, `Both` (`DataNode.type`)
* [x] If trace has `dataNodes.length > 1`, allow selecting individual `dataNode`
  * NOTE: requires changing `buildDataNodes(trace)` to `buildDataNodes(dataNode)`
  * fire traceSelection event with additional param `dataNodeId`
* [x] Smarter coherence when selecting different traces:
  * when clicking a trace, automatically choose the `dataNode` that participated in previous listing (if there is such a node)
* [x] Button Icons
* [x] Don't show same trace multiple times
* [ ] (future work) How to best visualize data flow in Call Graph (without a lot of extra coding effort)?

# New `ValueView`

* [x] Fix `ValueCollection.serialize` to only record "new data"
* [x] Add `DataNode.type` to distinguish between `Read`, `Write` and `Delete`
* [x] Upon any `Write`-type `DataNode`, make sure, we have enough information, to re-construct the final value
* [x] Do not `deserialize` anymore in `ValueRefCollection`
* [x] Remove `getTraceValue` function, and replace with `constructValueObjectShallow`
* [x] Produce time- and memory- optimized algorithm to re-construct the value of reference types for any `trace` using those partial recording
  * [x] if not object: get the actual `value` of a node from first node of same `valueId`
  * [x] if object: get the actual value by taking the first node's value, and then apply all `Write` + `Delete` operations that followed that value
* [x] Add two inline buttons to each value
  * [x] "Go to write trace" (the latest write of that value before currently selected `DataNode`)
  * [x] "Go to value creation" (go to first `DataNode` of same `valueId`)
* [ ] future-work: Add `constructValueObjectFull` for rendering/exporting features


# Bugs
* [x] `DebugTDNode` displays the wrong `TraceType` name
* [x] `ValueTDNode` always displays `undefined` -> make sure `dataProviderUtil` uses `dataNode` to get `value` and `valueId`, not `trace`
* [x] first `DataFlowNode` displayed in `DataFlowView` is incorrect when selecting `=` in `var x = 3 + 5`
  * should be `3 + 5` but is `3`
* [x] `undefined` values don't have a `valueId`
  * [x] test with `calls0.js`: during first call of `f`, investigate its parameters `a` and `b`'s `valueId`
    * NOTE: same with `g`'s second parameter
* [x] When using `getCallerTraceOfContext`, we cannot be sure if it is the BCE of the current context or not. E.g.: when inside the callback of `Array.map`, it would return the BCE of `Array.map`, which is not the actual caller of the callback's context.
  * In `RuntimeDataProvider`, replace use of `getCallerTraceOfContext` with a new utility function `getOwnCallerTraceOfContext`
  * [x] add new `getFunctionDefinitionTrace(contextId)`
    * Get the callee of the function via `bceTrace.data.calleeTid`
    * Return the first trace by `callee -> valueId` which has `TraceType.FunctionDe{finition,claration}`
  * NOTE: `getOwnCallerTraceOfContext` calls `getCallerTraceOfContext`, but then returns `null`, if the callee (a function object) is not that function (i.e. context):
  * See [peekBCECheckCallee](https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/blob/slicing/dbux-runtime/src/data/dataUtil.js)
  * Get `functionTrace = getFunctionDefinitionTrace(contextId);`
  * Return null if `functionTrace` does not exist or its `staticTrace.data.staticContextId` does not match the context's `staticContextId`
  * NOTE2: This is to avoid trying to connect data between caller and function, where the caller is not the actual function (e.g. `Array.map(f)`)


# Trace all files, even in `node_modules`

* [ ] Change default babel `include` behavior to include all
* [ ] Add package `blacklist` to `@dbux/cli`
* [ ] Make sure, `@dbux/cli` properly instruments all modules, even if they were used by the `@dbux/cli` itself
  * Might have to consider doing what `NYC` did instead
  * See https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/issues/513
* [ ] add some analytical tools to better understand:
  * which modules were loaded and when
  * which modules were require'd/imported vs. which modules were actually instrumented
  * which modules are not instrumented

# Data flow involving function calls

When a function is called, we want to add edges to data flow graph:

* [Parameters and arguments] from `CallExpression` arguments to `Param`s
  * [x] basics
  * [x] add `SpreadElement` support [es6]
  * [ ] add `RestElement` support [es6]
* [ ] capture function closure variable `declarationTid`s
  * NOTE: else, local-scope variables inside loops will share a single `declarationTid` just like a hoisted `var`, but they actually lead to one copy per iteration
* [ ] for that, we also need to take care of `bind`, `call`, `apply` etc...

We can do that in post-processing using the following procedures.
We assume:
  * `callTrace`, `callStaticTrace` and `callId` to be the `BCE`'s trace, staticTrace and traceId
  * `contextId` to be that of the called function

NOTE: Built-ins don't have a `context` and thus will require a different approach (see below)

## Return value

When encountering `CallExpressionResult`:

* [x] add data flow from `ReturnArgument` to `CallExpressionResult`

Alorithm:

1. `returnTraceId` = id of first (and only) `ReturnArgument` trace of `contextId`.
1. Set `CallExpressionResult`'s `input = [returnTraceId];`

* Consider `ExecutionContextCollection.setParamInputs` for reference.
* [x] test: `CallExpressionResult` should have a `valueId`
  * e.g. in `mix1.js`, `const b = o.f()` should be value-traceable
* [x] #537

## Parameters and arguments

See [ExecutionContextCollection.setParamInputs](https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/tree/master/dbux-data/src/RuntimeDataProvider.js).



# Data Flow Graph Instrumentation Basics

* es5
  * [x] Declare + define variables
  * [x] `CallExpression` + `BCE`
  * [x] `FunctionDeclaration`
  * [x] `FunctionExpression`
  * [x] `ArithmeticExpression`
  * [x] MemberExpression rvals
  * [x] MemberExpression lvals
  * [x] `{Object,Array}Expression`
  * [x] `UpdateExpression`
  * [x] `TemplateLiteral`
  * [x] `IfStatement`
  * [x] `SwitchStatement`
  * [x] `SwitchCase`
  * [x] `ConditionalExpression`
  * [x] `SequenceExpression`
  * [x] `ThrowStatement`
  * [x] `CatchClause`
  * [x] `WhileStatement`
  * [x] `DoWhileLoop`
  * [x] `ForStatement`
  * [ ] `ForInStatement`
  * [x] `undefined`, `NaN`, `Infinity`
  * [x] `this`
  * [x] fix value of `AssignmentExpression`, if `operator !== '='`
  * [ ] variable redeclaration in same scope (`addOwnDeclarationTrace`)
  * [ ] `arguments` (https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/issues/542)
  * [ ] global `declarationTid`s
  * [x] handle `module` + `module.exports` properly
    * [ ] establish data link between: `require` <-> `{module.,}exports`
  * [x] `delete o[x]`
  * [ ] `typeof`
* es6
  * [x] default parameters
  * [x] `ArrowFunctionExpression`
  * [x] `ObjectMethod`
    * [ ] `kind = get`, `kind = set`
  * [x] `SpreadElement` (`Function`, `ObjectExpression`, `ArrayExpression`)
  * [ ] `import` <-> `export`
  * [x] `Class{Expression,Declaration}`
    * [x] `ClassProperty`
    * [x] `ClassMethod`
    * [x] private members (NOTE: private members do not support dynamic access)
    * [ ] instance and prop initializers should run in the context of the ctor
    * [x] `super`
  * [ ] `ForOfStatement`
  * [x] `async` functions
  * [ ] `generator` functions
  * [ ] `Decorator`
  * Destructuring assignments
    * [ ] `ObjectPattern`
    * [ ] `ArrayPattern`
    * [ ] `AssignmentPattern`
    * [ ] `RestElement`
* [ ] built-ins (https://github.com/Domiii/dbux/issues/543)


# Value identity

Compute two new ids:

* [x] `dataNode.accessId`
* [x] `dataNode.valueId` (`getValueId`)

"Value identity" refers to a uid (`valueId`) that can uniquely identify a value:

* For `object`, `array`, `function` ("reference types" or "object types")
  * It is `dataNode.refId`
  * `!!refId` is always `true`
  * NOTEs:
    * `refId` is assigned in `runtime`.
    * It is the `traceId` that first recorded that object.
* For non-"object types", we, similarly, want to determine the `traceId` of when that value first came into existence.
  * Consider that many traces just access and move existing values, and do not actually create new values.
  * The algorithm is explained in [getValueId](#getValueId).
  * `!!refId` is always `false`

## `inputs`

* [x] Fix up `inputs`:  let `runtime` record `nodeId` (instead of `traceId`)
* [x] Fix up `Value Identitiy` algorithm to use `dataNodeId` instead of `traceId`

## ReferencedIdentifier vs. MemberExpression

* any `ReferencedIdentifier` refers to a variable name
  * -> `dataNode.varAccess` contains `declarationTid` (`traceId` that declared (or first recorded) the variable)
  * `accessId = makeUid(declarationTid)`
* any `ME` (`MemberExpression`) refers to accessing some object's (or other value, such as `int` or `string`) property
  * example: `f(x)[g(y)]`, where `object` = `f(x)` and `property` = `g(y)`
  * `varAccess` consists of:
    *  `objTid` (`traceId` of `object`)
    *  `prop` (value of `property`)
  * `accessId = makeUid(${getValueId(objTid)}#${prop})`

* TODO: `makeUid` should use a `Map` to convert that string into a number; to more easily maintain `AccessIdIndex`

## getValueId


Goal: Write `getValueId` function -
```js
function getValueId(dataNodeId) { ... }
```

We can compute `valueId` by post-processing in `DataNodeCollection.postAddRaw`.
Once computed, we want to store it in `dataNode.valueId`.

If a `value` is an object (that is, if it has a `refId`), return the first `traceId` of same `refId`.

If a `value` is not an object, the algorithm is based on each `DataNode`'s `Trace`'s `TraceType`, as follows:

* Default
  * Steps
    * -> if `staticTrace.dataNode.isNew`: `valueIdentity = traceId`
    * -> else if `inputs.length > 0`: `valueIdentity = getValueId(inputs[0])`
    * -> else: lookup last entry *before this one* in `DataNodesByAccessIdIndex` by `dataNode.accessId`
  * affected `TraceType`s include (but not limited to):
    * `Literal`
      * NOTE: always new
    * `Declaration`
      * NOTE: always implies a "new" `undefined` value (if not initialized)
    * `ExpressionResult`, `ExpressionValue`
      * who? `ArithmeticExpression`
    * `CallExpressionResult`
      * Post-processed to get `inputs`. See `Return value` section above.
      * Does not have `inputs` if (i) call did not return a value, or (ii) if we were not able to trace function correctly.
    * `Param`
      *  Post-processed to get `inputs`. See `Parameters and arguments` section above.
    * `WriteVar`
    * `WriteME`
    * `ReturnArgument`, `ThrowArgument`, `AwaitArgument`
    * `Identifier`, `ME` (`MemberExpression`)
      * Does not have `inputs`. Always has `accessId`.
* `BeforeCallExpression` -> same as `CallExpressionResult` (resolve in `CallExpressionResult`)
  * -> don't assign a `valueIdentity`.
  * NOTE: special handling in UI - `BCE` rendering should (for the most part) reflect `CallExpressionResult`

# More Future Work

## Trace object keys as data

* trace always, even if not computed
* if `!computed`, isNew = true, when key is added to object the first time
* if `computed`, isNew = false, and property is input
  * this `DataNode`'s `ValueIdentity` has 2 parents, making `Data Flow View` less intuitive
* key becomes rval via: `for-in`, `Object.keys`, `Object.entries`, etc.

issue.title: Fix CallGraph FocusController bugs

repository.name: dbux
repository.description: Dbux is an Integrated Debugging Environment (IDbE) and Omniscient Debugger that visualizes the JS runtime and aims at making it interactive for the developer. Currently working on the data flow graph, which should help answer the age-old question: "Why is that darn value just not what I want it to be?"

issue.body:
## Note

There is always a problem that `FocusController` tries to `focus` on some node right after we set the nodes' state. And yet we don't have a proper way(a Promise) to check if the DOM element is revealed. Thus, adding `await sleep(100)` before `focus` is a simple hackfix, even though **it might be a bad idea**.

Btw, the first problem "Cannot hide/unhide nodes anymore" is a side effect of this. I used to log a DOM element in the error logger of `FocusController`, which leads to an error `Uncaught DOMException: Failed to execute 'postMessage' on 'Window': A DOMDivElement could not be cloned` and breaks the `postMessage`.
Maybe it's a good practice to ensure parameters passing into log functions are strings.

#485

issue.title: Optimize Call Graph to deal with 50+k nodes per root

labels.name: performance
labels.description: Performance of runtime analysis tools can be quite a nuisance.

issue.body:
* [ ] Things get too slow when a call graph root has many descendants. Test this with Chart.js#2. There are 40+k descendants in some of the roots.
  * Make sure to use the right settings so that things don't slow down to a grinding halt:
    * Run without debugging ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/111025465-4a47bc80-841f-11eb-84ed-526f76aeba7e.png)
    * in `dbux-runtime\src\RuntimeMonitor.js` set `tracesDisabled` from `0` to `1`
  * [x] When working with such a root or its children, things get extremely slow. Find a way to fix this.
* [x] Do some preliminary performance profiling
  * Turns out, it can render the graph roots real quick (about 1 second).
  * After the first second, it will asynchronously keep adding everything else for some 10-20 seconds (16s in my case). While doing that, the Graph view is interactive, but too laggy to use.
  * Summary: Total time spent running our code = 11.1s
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110964668-63545d00-838e-11eb-92e5-963453235b8f.png)
  * Flamegraph (while building graph initially; after a Graph view restart):
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110962576-15d6f080-838c-11eb-80e4-42ddf9a1e733.png)
  * Tasks: This indicates, that the rasterizer thread is probably a bottleneck. (because we are adding that many nodes to HTML)
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110963402-fd1b0a80-838c-11eb-8c65-e1ba28cc7eb0.png)
  * Scripting breakdown (Total Time)
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110963847-8599ab00-838d-11eb-9b91-23eaff509c9b.png)
  * Scripting breakdown (Self Time)
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110964034-b5e14980-838d-11eb-949c-89b3a06f9f01.png)
  * Confirmed: HTML rendering takes a lot of time (half of the total time spent (11.1s))
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110965866-9d722e80-838f-11eb-96e2-8fc9b84e93b6.png)

* Maybe clear up some inconsistencies in above analysis result:
  * [ ] Why does `compileHtmlElement` have three very different numbers?
    * `Self Time = 2.7s`, `Total Time = 4.2s` and the time spent inside it's `template.html = html` line is `5.8s`
    * Maybe I made a mistake recording it? Maybe we should start by repeating the analysis one more time to confirm.




## Improve performance

* [x] Lazy load for all nodes.

* Other possible ideas:
  * New "omission node" feature:
    * If a context of same `staticContextId` has already been rendered within the same root (let's call them "repeated contexts"), add an omission node instead.
    * For any other "repeated context" that is either (i) a child of, or (ii) is following (on the timeline) an "omission node" : merge into the omission node.
  * We might have to lazy-load all layers, not just the root layer... ?
  * Maybe reducing `components`/`controllers` can help a little bit (but probably not much)

issue.body:
* [ ] Things get too slow when a call graph root has many descendants. Test this with Chart.js#2. There are 40+k descendants in some of the roots.
  * Make sure to use the right settings so that things don't slow down to a grinding halt:
    * Run without debugging ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/111025465-4a47bc80-841f-11eb-84ed-526f76aeba7e.png)
    * in `dbux-runtime\src\RuntimeMonitor.js` set `tracesDisabled` from `0` to `1`
  * [x] When working with such a root or its children, things get extremely slow. Find a way to fix this.
* [x] Do some preliminary performance profiling
  * Turns out, it can render the graph roots real quick (about 1 second).
  * After the first second, it will asynchronously keep adding everything else for some 10-20 seconds (16s in my case). While doing that, the Graph view is interactive, but too laggy to use.
  * Summary: Total time spent running our code = 11.1s
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110964668-63545d00-838e-11eb-92e5-963453235b8f.png)
  * Flamegraph (while building graph initially; after a Graph view restart):
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110962576-15d6f080-838c-11eb-80e4-42ddf9a1e733.png)
  * Tasks: This indicates, that the rasterizer thread is probably a bottleneck. (because we are adding that many nodes to HTML)
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110963402-fd1b0a80-838c-11eb-8c65-e1ba28cc7eb0.png)
  * Scripting breakdown (Total Time)
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110963847-8599ab00-838d-11eb-9b91-23eaff509c9b.png)
  * Scripting breakdown (Self Time)
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110964034-b5e14980-838d-11eb-949c-89b3a06f9f01.png)
  * Confirmed: HTML rendering takes a lot of time (half of the total time spent (11.1s))
    ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/282899/110965866-9d722e80-838f-11eb-96e2-8fc9b84e93b6.png)

* Maybe clear up some inconsistencies in above analysis result:
  * [ ] Why does `compileHtmlElement` have three very different numbers?
    * `Self Time = 2.7s`, `Total Time = 4.2s` and the time spent inside it's `template.html = html` line is `5.8s`
    * Maybe I made a mistake recording it? Maybe we should start by repeating the analysis one more time to confirm.




## Improve performance

* [x] Lazy load for all nodes.

* Other possible ideas:
  * New "omission node" feature:
    * If a context of same `staticContextId` has already been rendered within the same root (let's call them "repeated contexts"), add an omission node instead.
    * For any other "repeated context" that is either (i) a child of, or (ii) is following (on the timeline) an "omission node" : merge into the omission node.
  * We might have to lazy-load all layers, not just the root layer... ?
  * Maybe reducing `components`/`controllers` can help a little bit (but probably not much)

events.body:
## Status
In PR #459 , I've fix some bug in algorithm of `resolveCallIds`, which makes `express#18` and `express#20` runnable.

## Problems
However, they get error again when reload them from log file, since `resolveErrorTraces` will change `trace.staticTraceId`(this time it resolves callIds with new staticTraceId).
In PR #457, I've disabled `Collection.postAdd` on deserialize, so this error is fixed after merging the two PR, but we still have to figure out "why can't we resolve callIds from new staticTraceId". This time the error has something to do with issue #346 (ThrowArgument has been traced twice so can't find BCE at the second time).

Solved in PR #459 , note that `PDP` and `RDP` have different save demands(`PDP` needs to save right after new data comes in, while `RDP` only wants to save all data when needed), so `serialize/deserialize` and `save/load` can not be merged easily.

Express#20 has long been fixed, and, while still dirty, `resolveCallIds` has been revised and its internal error reporting largely improved several times since.
Also, @MiccWan has done a great job, fixing up mentioned `RDP` and `PDP` issues.

## To reproduce
run a file and close the GraphView when adding new nodes

## Causes
If we close the view while it's adding new node, the client side update will not be finished, thus component will not be initialized.
Then if we tried to start the view, `WebViewWrapper.show()` will "RESTART" the ComponentManager and cause a `componentManager.silentShutdown()` thus makes a `Trying to dispose before initialized` error.

`WebViewWrapper.show` -> `WebViewWrapper.restart` ->  `WebViewWrapper._restartHost` -> `GraphWebView.startHost` -> `startGraphHost@dbux-graph-host/src/index.js` -> `reset` -> `componentManager.silentShutdown`

I don't think this should work in this way, maybe we should shutdown the componentManager on WebView disposed.
We can discuss on Monday, if you still have doubts then :)
